{"title_page": "Fuego (Eleni Foureira song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Fuego\n| cover      = Fuego_-_Eleni_Foureira.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Eleni Foureira]]\n| album      = Vasilissa (Platinum Edition)\n| released   = 9 March 2018\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[Folk-pop|Balkan pop-folk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/single/%CE%B5%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%BD%CE%B7-%CF%86%CE%BF%CF%85%CF%81%CE%B5%CE%B9%CF%81%CE%B1/fuego/|title=Fuego by Eleni Foureira|publisher=rateyourmusic.com}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 3:03\n| label      = {{hlist|Panik Records|[[Sony Music]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Alex P]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| prev_title = 2018 S'agapo\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Caramela\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|eDSgs6syrgg|\"Fuego\"}} }}\n{{Infobox song contest entry\n| embed       = yes\n| song        = {{flagicon|Cyprus}} \"Fuego\"\n| year        = 2018\n| country     = Cyprus\n| artist      = [[Eleni Foureira]]\n| genre       =\n| language    = English\n| composer    = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| lyricist    = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| place       = 2nd\n| points      = 436\n| place_semi  = 2nd\n| points_semi = 262\n| prev        = Gravity\n| prev_link   = Gravity (Hovig song)\n| next        = Replay\n| next_link   = Replay (Tamta song)\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Fuego'''\" is a song recorded by Greek-Albanian singer [[Eleni Foureira]]. It was [[Musical composition|composed]], [[Songwriting|written]] and [[Record production|produced]] by [[Alex Papaconstantinou]], Geraldo Sandell, Viktor Svensson, Anderz Wrethov and Didrick.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Cyprus: Eleni Foureira premieres the video of 'Fuego' |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eleni-foureira-releases-fuego-cyprus-entry-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=2 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe song [[Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|represented Cyprus]] in the [[2018 Eurovision Song Contest]] in [[Lisbon]], Portugal after being internally selected by the national broadcaster [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eleni Foureira to fly the flag for Cyprus with 'Fuego' |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eleni-foureira-to-represent-cyprus-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=1 February 2018}}</ref> The country reached second place in a field of twenty-six scoring a total of 436 points making the country's highest placement to date.\n\nThe accompanying [[music video]] for the song was premiered onto the official [[YouTube]] channel of the Eurovision Song Contest on 12 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eleni Foureira - Fuego - Cyprus - Official Music Video - Eurovision 2018 |url=https://eurovision.tv/video/eleni-foureira-fuego-cyprus-official-music-video-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Composition ===\n\n\"Fuego\" was entirely written and produced by [[Alex Papaconstantinou]], Geraldo Sandell, Viktor Svensson, Anderz Wrethov and Didrick. The song was described as a [[dance-pop]] song with [[Folk-pop|Balkan pop-folk]] elements while the melody employs the [[millennial whoop]] pattern. It was originally offered to Greek-Swedish singer [[Helena Paparizou]] and Greek-Georgian singer [[Tamta]] before being offered to Eleni Foureira.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/02/01/cyprus-eleni-foureira-officially-confirmed-eurovision-2018/|title=Cyprus: Eleni Foureira Officially Confirmed for Eurovision 2018|date=1 February 2018|publisher=Eurovoix|last=Farren|first=Neil}}</ref> A demo version of \"Fuego\" recorded by Paparizou was leaked online in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/04/02/cyprus-helena-paparizou-version-of-fuego-leaked/|title=Cyprus: Helena Paparizou Version of \"Fuego\" Leaked|date=2018-04-02|work=Eurovoix|access-date=2018-11-20|language=en-US}}</ref> The Spanish version of \"Fuego\" was translated by Natalis Ruby Rubero and Edwin Serrano.\n\n== At Eurovision ==\n\n=== Internal selection ===\n\n[[Eleni Foureira]] was announced as the Cypriot act for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018 contest]] on 25 January 2018 after weeks of rumours regarding the artist selection. However, this announcement was not by the Cypriot broadcaster, and was not official. On 1 February 2018, it was announced by the CyBC that the song Fuego would represent Cyprus at the 2018 contest with Eleni Foureira as the singer. The song title was announced to the public (although not confirmed by [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|CyBC]]) on 25 January 2018, and was composed by Greek-Swedish producer and songwriter [[Alex P]].  \n\n=== Lisbon ===\n{{Main|Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018}}\n\nThe [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|63rd edition]] of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] took place in [[Lisbon]], Portugal and consisted of two semi-finals on 8 and 10 May, and the grand final on 12 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eurovision Song Contest\u2013Lisbon 2018 |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> Each participating country, except the host country and the [[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big 5]], is required to qualify from one of two semi-finals to compete for the grand final.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Rules |url=https://eurovision.tv/about/rules |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nCyprus qualified for the grand final in second place with 262 points on 8 May 2018 ranking sixth by the jury's 89 points and first by the televote of 173 points.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Lisbon 2018: First Semi-Final\u2013Scoreboard |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018/first-semi-final/results/cyprus |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> In the grand final, it reached second place in a field of twenty-six with 436 points on 12 May 2018 placed fifth by the jury's 183 points and second by the televote of 253 points.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Lisbon 2018: Grand Final\u2013Detailed voting results |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018/grand-final/results |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> It is currently the country's highest placement in the Eurovision Song Contest to date.\n \n== In other Media ==\n\n[[Telemundo]] used the Spanish song as the official song for the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|FIFA Women's World Cup 2019]] in [[France]]. It was featured in the third and sixth episode of the second season of ''[[\u00c9lite (TV series)|\u00c9lite]]''.\n \n== Charts ==\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|35|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=23 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|10|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=1 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|France|70|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|81|songid=1739792|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 May 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Greece Airplay ([[IFPI Greece]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airplaychart.gr/index.php?ts=1527531222 |publisher=IFPI.gr |title=Official IFPI Airplay Chart |language=Greek |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611185151/http://ifpi.gr/airplay_el.html |archivedate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n| 14\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Greece Digital Singles ([[IFPI Greece]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifpi.gr/digital_el.html |publisher=IFPI.gr |title=Official IFPI Charts-Digital Singles Chart |language=Greek |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522132228/http://www.ifpi.gr/digital_el.html |archivedate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n| 50\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Israel ([[Media Forest]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediaforest.biz/WeeklyCharts/|title=Media Forest 20 13-05-18 19-05-18|publisher=[[Media Forest]]|accessdate=25 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002213912/http://www.mediaforest.biz/WeeklyCharts/|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|96|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 May 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Norway ([[VG-lista]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vglista.no/topplister/topp-20-single-2018-23/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 20 Single uke 23, 2018|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n| 16\n|-\n{{single chart|Polishdance|33|chartid=2794|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 August 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|18|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|30|date=20180518|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.es/listas/semana/3730-canciones-semana-20-2018|title=Top 100 Canciones \u2013 Semana 20: del 11.05.2018 al 17.05.2018|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|accessdate=23 May 2018|language=Spanish|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spain Airplay ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.es/listas/semana/3855-radio-semana-40-2018|title=TOP 50 - Lista de Radio Musical \u2014\u2014Semana 40: Del 29-09-2018 al 05-10-2018|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|accessdate=9 October 2018|language=Spanish|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/|title=Sverigetopplistan \u2013 Sveriges Officiella Topplista|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n| 14\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|46|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|64|date=20180518|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 May 2018}}\n|}<!-- Do not include the UK Download chart here, as it charted on the overall UK Singles Chart, which downloads contribute to. See [[WP:CHARTMATH]]. -->\n\n=== Year-end charts ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.es/documents/viewfile/185-top-100-canciones-2018|title=Top 100 Canciones + Streaming Anual 2018|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=23 February 2019|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| 70\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Spain|award=Platinum|artist=Mahmood|type=single|relyear=2018|certyear=2018|certmonth=07|title=Fuego|accessdate=29 March 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true|nosales=true}}\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download\n| title1 = Fuego\n| length1 = 3:03\n| title2 = Fuego\n| note2 = Spanish version\n| length2 = 3:03\n}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Various\n| 9 March 2018\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| A-P Records / Panik Records\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2018}}\n\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:Dance-pop songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Greece]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2018]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Alex P]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wrethov]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Fuego\n| cover      = Fuego_-_Eleni_Foureira.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Eleni Foureira]]\n| album      = Vasilissa (Platinum Edition)\n| released   = 9 March 2018\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[Folk-pop|Balkan pop-folk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/single/%CE%B5%CE%BB%CE%B5%CE%BD%CE%B7-%CF%86%CE%BF%CF%85%CF%81%CE%B5%CE%B9%CF%81%CE%B1/fuego/|title=Fuego by Eleni Foureira|publisher=rateyourmusic.com}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 3:03\n| label      = {{hlist|Panik Records|[[Sony Music]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Alex P]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| prev_title = 2018 S'agapo\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Caramela\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|eDSgs6syrgg|\"Fuego\"}} }}\n{{Infobox song contest entry\n| embed       = yes\n| song        = {{flagicon|Cyprus}} \"Fuego\"\n| year        = 2018\n| country     = Cyprus\n| artist      = [[Eleni Foureira]]\n| genre       =\n| language    = English\n| composer    = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| lyricist    = {{hlist|[[Alex Papaconstantinou]]|Geraldo Sandell|Viktor Svensson|Anderz Wrethov|Didrick}}\n| place       = 2nd\n| points      = 436\n| place_semi  = 2nd\n| points_semi = 262\n| prev        = Gravity\n| prev_link   = Gravity (Hovig song)\n| next        = Replay\n| next_link   = Replay (Tamta song)\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Fuego'''\" is a song recorded by Greek-Albanian singer [[Eleni Foureira]]. It was [[Musical composition|composed]], [[Songwriting|written]] and [[Record production|produced]] by [[Alex Papaconstantinou]], Geraldo Sandell, Viktor Svensson, Anderz Wrethov and Didrick.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Cyprus: Eleni Foureira premieres the video of 'Fuego' |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eleni-foureira-releases-fuego-cyprus-entry-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=2 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe song [[Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|represented Cyprus]] in the [[2018 Eurovision Song Contest]] in [[Lisbon]], Portugal after being internally selected by the national broadcaster [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eleni Foureira to fly the flag for Cyprus with 'Fuego' |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eleni-foureira-to-represent-cyprus-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=1 February 2018}}</ref> The country reached second place in a field of twenty-six scoring a total of 436 points making the country's highest placement to date.\n\nThe accompanying [[music video]] for the song was premiered onto the official [[YouTube]] channel of the Eurovision Song Contest on 12 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eleni Foureira - Fuego - Cyprus - Official Music Video - Eurovision 2018 |url=https://eurovision.tv/video/eleni-foureira-fuego-cyprus-official-music-video-eurovision-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English |date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Composition ===\n\n\"Fuego\" was entirely written and produced by [[Alex Papaconstantinou]], Geraldo Sandell, Viktor Svensson, Anderz Wrethov and Didrick. The song was described as a [[dance-pop]] song with [[Folk-pop|Balkan pop-folk]] elements while the melody employs the [[millennial whoop]] pattern. It was originally offered to Greek-Swedish singer [[Helena Paparizou]] and Greek-Georgian singer [[Tamta]] before being offered to Eleni Foureira.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/02/01/cyprus-eleni-foureira-officially-confirmed-eurovision-2018/|title=Cyprus: Eleni Foureira Officially Confirmed for Eurovision 2018|date=1 February 2018|publisher=Eurovoix|last=Farren|first=Neil}}</ref> A demo version of \"Fuego\" recorded by Paparizou was leaked online in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/04/02/cyprus-helena-paparizou-version-of-fuego-leaked/|title=Cyprus: Helena Paparizou Version of \"Fuego\" Leaked|date=2018-04-02|work=Eurovoix|access-date=2018-11-20|language=en-US}}</ref> The Spanish version of \"Fuego\" was translated by Natalis Ruby Rubero and Edwin Serrano.\n\n== At Eurovision ==\n\n=== Internal selection ===\n\n[[Eleni Foureira]] was announced as the Cypriot act for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018 contest]] on 25 January 2018 after weeks of rumours regarding the artist selection. However, this announcement was not by the Cypriot broadcaster, and was not official. On 1 February 2018, it was announced by the CyBC that the song Fuego would represent Cyprus at the 2018 contest with Eleni Foureira as the singer. The song title was announced to the public (although not confirmed by [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|CyBC]]) on 25 January 2018, and was composed by Greek-Swedish producer and songwriter [[Alex P]].  \n\n=== Lisbon ===\n{{Main|Cyprus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018}}\n\nThe [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|63rd edition]] of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] took place in [[Lisbon]], Portugal and consisted of two semi-finals on 8 and 10 May, and the grand final on 12 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Eurovision Song Contest\u2013Lisbon 2018 |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018 |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> Each participating country, except the host country and the [[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big 5]], is required to qualify from one of two semi-finals to compete for the grand final.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Rules |url=https://eurovision.tv/about/rules |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nCyprus qualified for the grand final in second place with 262 points on 8 May 2018 ranking sixth by the jury's 89 points and first by the televote of 173 points.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Lisbon 2018: First Semi-Final\u2013Scoreboard |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018/first-semi-final/results/cyprus |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> In the grand final, it reached second place in a field of twenty-six with 436 points on 12 May 2018 placed fifth by the jury's 183 points and second by the televote of 253 points.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |title=Lisbon 2018: Grand Final\u2013Detailed voting results |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018/grand-final/results |website=eurovision.tv |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref> It is currently the country's highest placement in the Eurovision Song Contest to date.\n \n== In other Media ==\n\n[[Telemundo]] used the Spanish song as the official song for the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|FIFA Women's World Cup 2019]] in [[France]]. It was featured in the third and sixth episode of the second season of ''[[\u00c9lite (TV series)|\u00c9lite]]''.\n \n== Charts ==\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|35|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=23 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|10|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=1 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|France|70|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|81|songid=1739792|artist=Eleni Foureira|song=Fuego|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 May 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Greece Airplay ([[IFPI Greece]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airplaychart.gr/index.php?ts=1527531222 |publisher=IFPI.gr |title=Official IFPI Airplay Chart |language=Greek |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611185151/http://ifpi.gr/airplay_el.html |archivedate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n| 14\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Greece Digital Singles ([[IFPI Greece]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifpi.gr/digital_el.html |publisher=IFPI.gr |title=Official IFPI Charts-Digital Singles Chart |language=Greek |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522132228/http://www.ifpi.gr/digital_el.html |archivedate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n| 50\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Israel ([[Media Forest]])<ref>{{cite web|url